Grupo Bimbo Data Exploration¶

Objective: Maximize sales, minimize returns

Planning a celebration is a balancing act of preparing just enough food to go around without being stuck eating the same leftovers for the next week. The key is anticipating how many guests will come. Grupo Bimbo must weigh similar considerations as it strives to meet daily consumer demand for fresh bakery products on the shelves of over 1 million stores along its 45,000 routes across Mexico.

def intersect_and_diff(df1,df2,col):
    trainags = set(df1[col].values)
    testags = set(df2[col].values)
    print("intersection: ", len(trainags.intersection(testags)))
    print("train: ", len(trainags))
    print("test: ", len(testags))
    print("difference d1/d2: ", len(trainags.difference(testags)))
    testdiff = testags.difference(trainags)
    print("difference d2/d1: ", len(testdiff))
    return testdiff

In [45]:
def select_random(a, num):
    index_array = np.arange(len(a))
    np.random.shuffle(index_array)
    return a[index_array[:num]]

There are more clients than routes, so we're going to use some tricks to append to the list of clients to exclude. We're taking clients from several bins of 10-wide. The following statement allows us to figure out how many clients to select at random.

In [ ]:
subset = clients.groupby("Cliente_ID").filter(lambda x: len(x) < 11 and len(x) > 1)
len(subset["Cliente_ID"].unique())

So let's start with an empty list and add clients of interest to those. The reason we take from bins is that the number of clients that appear once or twice is much larger, so a random pick wouldn't get the same ratio.
